## Readiness items

### 1. Custodian status (PHIPA s. 3)

- **What it requires**: identify whether your project is operated by a
  HIC (e.g., a regulated health professional, a hospital, a community
  health centre, a long-term care home, etc.) or is acting as an Agent
  of one (PHIPA s. 17). Vendors who are neither HICs nor Agents handle
  PHI only under contract.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in]`.
- **TBD**: written role declaration; lawyer review of the role
  classification; per-tenant role declarations if you serve multiple
  HICs.

### 2. Agent obligations (PHIPA s. 17, s. 10)

- **What it requires**: Agents act on behalf of a HIC and may only
  collect, use, and disclose PHI as permitted by their HIC's mandate
  and PHIPA. The HIC remains accountable for the Agent's acts.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: written terms between
  {{PROJECT_NAME}} and the HIC delineating the Agent relationship;
  the scope of authority; the safeguards the Agent commits to]`.
- **TBD**: Information Manager Agreement template (where applicable
  under PHIPA s. 10).

### 3. Knowledgeable consent (PHIPA s. 18)

- **What it requires**: collection, use, and disclosure of PHI requires
  knowledgeable consent — the individual knows the purposes and the
  consequences of giving or withholding consent. Some uses and
  disclosures are permitted without consent (PHIPA s. 39–s. 50);
  others always require it.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: consent flow on intake;
  separate consent for purposes outside core care, such as research,
  marketing, or analytics]`.
- **TBD**: consent UI for secondary uses; consent-version tracking;
  withdrawal mechanism reachable from the patient/client portal.

### 4. Lockbox / express instructions (PHIPA s. 19, s. 37)

- **What it requires**: individuals may give express instructions not
  to use or disclose PHI for health-care purposes (often called the
  "lockbox" right). Limited exceptions apply (e.g., when withholding
  would result in significant harm).
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: how an individual can
  mark a portion of their record withheld from a specific
  practitioner or care context; how providers see and act on
  lockbox markers]`.
- **TBD**: lockbox UI; technical enforcement (data-access predicates);
  override-and-flag flow for the s. 37(1)(a) "significant harm"
  exception.

### 5. Limiting collection, use, disclosure (PHIPA s. 30, s. 31, s. 32)

- **What it requires**: collect, use, and disclose only what is
  necessary for a lawful purpose; do not use or disclose PHI if
  de-identified information would serve the purpose.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: data-minimization
  practice — what fields collected for which purposes; where
  de-identified or aggregated data substitutes for raw PHI]`.

### 6. Safeguards (PHIPA s. 12)

- **What it requires**: take reasonable steps to protect PHI against
  theft, loss, and unauthorized use or disclosure. Includes
  administrative, technical, and physical safeguards.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: TLS in transit;
  encryption at rest; access controls (role-based, attribute-based);
  audit logging (see [`audit-log-requirements.md`](audit-log-requirements.md));
  secret management; vulnerability management]`.
- **TBD**: external penetration test cadence; tabletop incident
  exercise; vendor-security-review schedule.

### 7. Audit log of PHI access (PHIPA s. 10.1)

- **What it requires**: maintain, audit, and monitor an electronic
  record of all accesses to records of PHI in electronic form.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: see
  [`audit-log-requirements.md`](audit-log-requirements.md).
- **TBD**: log retention policy (clinical records commonly retained
  10+ years per College guidelines; align audit logs); access-log
  export capability for individuals (PHIPA s. 52 right of access
  extends to logs in some interpretations).

### 8. Breach notification (PHIPA s. 12.2)

- **What it requires**: notify affected individuals at the first
  reasonable opportunity if PHI is stolen, lost, or used or disclosed
  without authority; notify the IPC in defined circumstances.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: see
  [`breach-response.md`](breach-response.md). The IPC's breach
  protocol is at
  <https://www.ipc.on.ca/en/health-organizations/responding-to-a-privacy-breach/privacy-breach-protocol>
  (accessed 2026-05-12).
- **TBD**: notification templates (affected individual, IPC, HIC if
  this project is an Agent); rehearsed escalation path.

### 9. Annual statistical reporting (PHIPA O. Reg. 224/17)

- **What it requires**: HICs are required to submit annual aggregate
  privacy-breach statistics to the IPC by March 1 of the following
  calendar year, regardless of whether individual breaches were
  reported at the time.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: who owns the annual
  submission and how breach-register data is rolled up]`.
- **TBD**: calendar reminder; submission rehearsal in Q1 of the first
  full year.

### 10. Individual right of access (PHIPA s. 52)

- **What it requires**: an individual has a right of access to a record
  of their PHI, subject to enumerated exceptions. Response is required
  within 30 days, extendable to 60 days in specified circumstances.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: access-request channel
  and SLA; format of disclosed record]`.

### 11. Individual right of correction (PHIPA s. 55)

- **What it requires**: an individual may request correction; the HIC
  must respond within 30 days, granting or providing reasons for
  refusal.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in]`.

### 12. Disclosure for research (PHIPA s. 44)

- **What it requires**: disclosure of PHI for research requires a
  research plan approved by a Research Ethics Board (REB) and a
  research agreement, except where the disclosure is otherwise
  permitted.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in or "not applicable"
  if no research use]`.

### 13. Data residency expectation

- **What it requires**: PHIPA does not strictly mandate Canadian
  residency, but practical expectations (College guidance, HIC
  preferences, patient expectations) favour Canadian residency where
  feasible.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: `[fill in: cloud region(s) where
  PHI is stored; any cross-border processing]`.
- **TBD**: subprocessor DPAs confirming residency or contractual
  safeguards where data crosses the border.

### 14. Information-Practice statement (PHIPA s. 16)

- **What it requires**: each HIC must make readily available to the
  public a written statement of their information practices.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: see
  [`privacy-policy.md`](privacy-policy.md).
- **TBD**: counsel review.

### 15. Complaint pathway (PHIPA s. 56, s. 57)

- **What it requires**: a complaint mechanism within the organization
  and access to the IPC for unresolved complaints.
- **How {{PROJECT_NAME}} meets it**: contact `[fill in: privacy
  contact]`. Escalation to the IPC.

## Lawyer-review checklist

- [ ] HIC vs. Agent role declared and documented.
- [ ] Privacy / Information Practice statement reviewed.
- [ ] Consent flows reviewed (knowledgeable consent + lockbox + research).
- [ ] Breach response runbook reviewed (notification timing, IPC contact,
      HIC coordination if Agent).
- [ ] Access-request and correction-request flows reviewed.
- [ ] Audit log content reviewed against PHIPA s. 10.1.
- [ ] Subprocessor agreements reviewed for PHI-handling vendors.
- [ ] Annual statistical reporting calendar in place.

